The enclosed test files were created to test the fix from 2026-04-10 for incorrect timing of form curves due to confusion in time units (whole notes or seconds).
These also serve as illustration of how each form parameter sinusoid affects the music.

To run the tests, run make
make
This produced the textmidi files, then the MIDI files.  Play the MIDI files and listen to the entire 1-minute pieces.
testcgmmeanpitch : the pitch (MIDI key) starts very low, then over 30 seconds rises to the top of the range, then falls slowly to the bottom again at 60 seconds.
testcgmrangepitch : the mean pitch is about mid-range; the range of pitch starts very narrowly, then spreads out to  most of the range at 30 seconds, then contracts 
to one note at 60 seconds.
testcgmmeanrhythm : the rhythm starts very fast, and slowly lengthens to 1 second per note at 30 seconds, then slowly gets shorter again until the end at 60 seconds.
testcgmrangerhythm : the rhythm is very regular, and gradually gets more syncopated and random until 30 seconds, when it slowly becomes very regular at 60 seconds.
testcgmmeandynamic: the loudness, velocity, or dynamic, starts very quietly and gradually loudens until 30 seconds, then fades away until 60 seconds.
testcgmrangedynamic: the loudness is medium loud at the beginning, but gradually get more varied or syncopated seeming until 30 seconds, when it gradually
gets more mundane, same, and routine until 60 seconds.
testcgmtexture: start with one line, then gradually add another voice and another every 15 seconds or so until 30 seconds, then gradually drop voices 
like Haydn's Farewell symphony.
textcgmscramble: test the timing of arrangements.  A single voices plays from a 4-voice ensemble, but voice rotation is used to bring a different track
forward about every 15 seconds.
2026-04-11 TEJ
